The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, April 13, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 12: Industrial growth shot up to 7.4 per cent in February, giving a further boost to the governments India shining campaign ahead of the Lok Sabha polls. Industry grew at 6.7 per cent in April-February, 2003-04, against 5.8 per cent in the year-ago period, according to estimates by Central Statistical Organisation. The growth has been mainly fuelled by the manufacturing and machinery and transport equipment sectors.																								 New Delhi, April 12: Major steel makers associations said they would not export hot-rolled coil at the cost of the domestic market. The Indian Steel Alliance said the rise in steel prices was mainly due to increase in input prices.																								 Calcutta, April 12: The total holding of promoters in Bombay Dyeing and Manufacturing Company has increased by 0.53 per cent in 2003-04. The variation in percentage holding was due to extinguishment of shares after buy-back. 																								 Mumbai, April 12: Finolex Industries Ltd has posted a 12.16 per cent growth in net profit at Rs 90.16 crore in 2003-04 compared with Rs 80.38 crore in 2002-03. The board has recommended a 20 per cent final dividend at Rs 2 per share for 2003-04. 																								 Mumbai, April 12: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has initiated adjudication proceedings against Varinder Gupta and Mayadevi Polycot Ltd for violating its takeover regulations while increasing their stake in Trident Alcochem Ltd.
